INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:Detected 12 issues:
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [5] open_ended: forward() assumes that both the input and all module parameters/buffers are already on XPU. In KernelBench-style execution this is not guaranteed: get_inputs() returns a CPU tensor, y = torch.empty_like(x) will allocate CPU output, and the Triton launch will receive CPU pointers. This is correctness-critical and violates the XPU device handling constraint.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] redundant_computation: When WINDOWS_PER_PROG > 1, attention is computed as a dense [N*WPP, N*WPP] matrix and cross-window entries are masked only after the QK dot. For WPP=8 this computes 128x128 attention scores even though the true attention is eight independent 16x16 blocks. The same waste occurs in RPE loads, softmax exponentials, and the attention-probability times V dot.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [5] fusion_register_pressure: The kernel fuses the entire Swin block, including two LayerNorms, Q/K/V projections, attention, projection, FC1, GELU, and FC2, into a single program. For WPP=8, live tensors include q/k/v, a 128x128 attention matrix, a 128x128 FC1 activation, multiple weight matrices, and residuals. This is very likely to cause GRF pressure, spills, and low occupancy on Intel XPU.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] long_liveness: All weight matrices and their transposed versions are loaded near the top of the kernel, long before some of them are used. For example fc1_w/fc2_w and their transposes are live across the whole LayerNorm1, QKV, attention, projection, residual, and LayerNorm2 sequence. This unnecessarily extends register lifetime.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [4] high_register_pressure: The MLP materializes h_act and h_gelu as [NTOT, HIDDEN]. With WPP=8 this is 128x128 elements, in addition to the live [NTOT,C] tensors and attention matrix. This is a large per-program temporary for an XPU kernel.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_packed_transpose: Every program loads row-major PyTorch Linear weights and transposes them in the Triton kernel using tl.trans. This is repeated for q, k, v, proj, fc1, and fc2. These transposed RHS layouts are invariant across forward calls in inference and should be pre-packed once.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] suboptimal_autotune_configs: The autotune space omits WINDOWS_PER_PROG=1, even though WPP>1 causes block-diagonal attention to be computed as dense cross-window attention. The configs also do not explore XPU-specific GRF mode variants.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [3] missing_grf_mode: The Triton configs do not set grf_mode='256'. This kernel has large tiles and high live state, so Intel XPU may benefit from 256-GRF mode to reduce spills or enable better scheduling.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] sigmoid_slow_exp: The softmax uses tl.exp on the attention scores. On Intel XPU, exp2 is typically faster. The same transformation commonly used for sigmoid also applies to softmax exponentials.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] suboptimal_algorithm: Q, K, and V are computed as three separate dot products with the same left operand ln1_h. This rereads/reuses the same activation tile three times and launches three dot operations where one wider QKV projection would be more efficient.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [1] common_subexpression: The expression nt_idx % N is already computed as tok_local, but the RPE load recomputes nt_idx[None, :] % N.
INFO:xe_forge.pipeline:  [2] manual_pointer_arithmetic: The kernel uses manual flattened pointer arithmetic for X/Y, weights, and RPE. This is error-prone and prevents Triton from using block pointer boundary semantics and layout information.
